'''''Here Come the Brides''''' is the debut album by [[Brides of Destruction]] released via [[Sanctuary Records]] on March 9, 2004. It is their most successful album being the only one to have a charting on the [[Billboard 200]], it is also the only album that features founder [[Nikki Sixx]] who would leave the band to rejoin [[M<U+00F6>tley Cr<U+00FC>e]] for their reunion tour in 2005.
The album's only single, "Shut The Fuck Up" failed to chart due to little airplay. "Only Get So Far" was originally written by Nikki Sixx for [[Tim McGraw]] and [[Faith Hill]].

==Background and recording==
Brides of Destruction was formed by [[Nikki Sixx]] and [[Tracii Guns]] in Los Angeles 2002 initially with the name '''Cockstar''' after [[M<U+00F6>tley Cr<U+00FC>e]] went on hiatus and Tracii left [[L.A. Guns]]. The lineup was rounded off with singer [[London LeGrand]], keyboardist [[Adam Hamilton (musician)|Adam Hamilton]] and [[Kris Kohls]] of [[Adema]] on drums. They were advised by radio programmers that the name '''Cockstar''' wouldn't be announced on air. They briefly adopted the moniker '''Motordog''' before settling on '''Brides of Destruction''' after it was suggested to Sixx by a friend.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=6780 MOTORDOG Becomes BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION - Oct. 11, 2002]</ref><ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=7675 BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION's NIKKI SIXX Discusses Band Moniker - Nov. 19, 2002]</ref> Hamilton left shortly after and was replaced by [[John Corabi]], also formerly of M<U+00F6>tley Cr<U+00FC>e, who became the band's second guitarist. They entered the studio with producer Stevo Bruno to begin recording. Kohls left the bend in early 2003 but is still credited in the album for the songs "I Got a Gun", "Natural Born Killers", "Revolution" and "Only Get So Far" despite Sixx stating that his replacement, [[Scot Coogan]], had re-recorded the drum parts for them:

{{cquote|'A little update to some of you. We [BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION] just finished the last set of songs... We went in with six, came out with five done, plus the four from before. We have three that just need a little work to finish as well. Scot [Coogan] played drums to the older songs replacing [former B.O.D. and current ADEMA drummer] Kris Kohl's drums so it all sounds like it's from the same band/sessions.'<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=9472 M<U+00D6>TLEY CR<U+00DC>E's SIXX: We Won't Ask Old Fans To Purchase Upcoming Reissues - Feb. 5, 2003]</ref>}}

After recording his guitar parts for all the songs, Corabi left the Brides stating he wanted to pursue a solo career as his reasons. In an interview years later Corabi cited some tension with Tracii and little writing input contributing to his decision to leave:

{{cquote|'To be perfectly honest with you, I get along with Nikki [Sixx] splendidly, but when I left the band I told Nikki that there was gonna be some egos involved, I don't wanna say who, but I just said there's a member in this band that I just do not get along with, that I do not write well with. First of all they basically told me that they don't need me to write at all, so I was like I'm not into that situation, and I told Nikki "Dude, I love you to death. I known that you and I can write a great record and so I'm out.". And as it turned out he just sent Bruce [Kulick] an email like a week ago and said "Tell Corabi I'm really sorry about the Brides of Destruction thing and he was right." Because Nikki is having an issue now with the person that I was having an issue with<U+2026> So we'll just leave it at that.'<ref>[http://www.musicmight.com/artist/united+states/california/los+angeles/brides+of+destruction Metal Rules John Corabi Interview]</ref><ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=11043 JOHN CORABI Leaves BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION - Apr. 2, 2003]</ref>}}

Sixx's future [[Sixx:A.M.]] bandmate [[James Michael]] features on the album, co-writing "Brace Yourself", "Natural Born Killers" and "Only Get So Far". Justin Nichols and Grammy nominated songwriter Kevin Kadish are also given writing credits on the song "Life" which sees drummer Scot Coogan performing lead vocals. After recording was finished, the album was mixed by [[Grammy]] Award winning producer and mixer [[Steve Thompson (musician)|Steve Thompson]]. Initially it looked like the album would only see a [[Japan]]ese release after signing a deal with Universal Records and failing to find a label for an [[United States|American]]/[[Europe]]an release. Due to this it looked likely the band were to split<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=14301 BRIDES BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION: Is The End Near? - Aug. 9, 2003]</ref> until they signed a deal with [[Sanctuary Records]]<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=16712 BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION Sign With SANCTUARY RECORDS - Nov. 14, 2003]</ref> and set a release date that was pushed back a number of times<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=17094 BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION Set North American Release Date For Debut Album - Dec. 2, 2003]</ref> eventually being released on March 9, 2004. The band chose "Shut the Fuck Up" as their first single and recorded a video with director Paul Brown.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=19114 BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION Film Video For 'Shut the Fuck Up' - Feb. 11, 2004]</ref> The song was chosen as a protest against politicians discussing the war against terror. Despite the fact that the track was edited for radio, the song did not receive as much airplay as the band would have liked and the track failed to chart.

==Release==
Upon release, Here Come the Brides chart at number 92 on the [[Billboard 200]] selling 13,694 copies.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=20450 SOUNDSCAN Report: TESLA, BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION, KATAKLYSM, DECAPITATED - Mar. 17, 2004]</ref> The band announced the '''Honeymoon From Hell''' [[United States Of America|US]] tour to support the album with support from [[Amen (band)|Amen]] and [[Living Things (band)|Living Things]]. They also played at festivals in [[Europe]] such as [[Download Festival|Download]] in the [[United Kingdom|UK]], [[Metaltown Festival|Metaltown]] in [[Sweden]] and supported [[Alice Cooper]] for a couple of shows in [[Norway]] and Sweden.<ref>[http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=20671 BRIDES OF DESTRUCTION Announce 'Honeymoon From Hell' Tour Dates - Mar. 23, 2004]</ref>

==Critical reception==
